{{Refimprove|date=November 2013}} {{Infobox magazine | image_file = Shape Tisdale.jpg | image_size = 210px | image_alt = | image_caption = A cover of ''Shape'', featuring [[Ashley Tisdale]], January 2009 | editor = Elizabeth Goodman Artis | editor_title = | previous_editor = Tara Kraft | staff_writer = | frequency = 10 issues per year | total_circulation= 1,568,055<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcas3.accessabc.com/ecirc/magtitlesearch.asp|title=eCirc for Consumer Magazines |work=[[Audit Bureau of Circulations (North America)|Audit Bureau of Circulations]]|accessdate=April 28, 2012}}</ref> | circulation_year= December 2011 | category = | company = [[Meredith Corporation|Meredith]] | publisher = | founded = 1981 | country = [[United States]] | based = [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles|Woodland Hills]], [[California]] | language = English | website = {{URL|http://www.shape.com}} | issn = 0744-5121 }} '''''Shape''''' is a monthly [[English language]] [[Physical fitness|fitness]] [[magazine]] started by [[Weider Publications]] in 1981,<ref>{{cite web|title=Magazines in Alphabetical Order|url=http://guides.library.harvard.edu/schlesinger_womens_magazines|work=Radcliffe Institute|accessdate=October 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Top 100 U.S. Magazines by Circulation|url=http://www.psaresearch.com/images/TOPMAGAZINES.pdf|work=PSA Research Center|accessdate=February 6, 2016}}</ref> founded by Christine MacIntyre (a pioneer in women's free weight fitness) and became the number one women's fitness magazine. At that time, Weider Enterprises consisted primarily of the bodybuilding magazine ''Muscle & Fitness''. Joe Weider and Christine MacIntyre had differing views of how to present ''Shape'', Weider endorsing a less journalistic and more commercial approach to articles, MacIntyre endorsing a more academic, doctor-based magazine. Weider also endorsed a sexier approach to editorial while MacIntyre endorsed a healthier look for women, eschewing sexiness in the models and the copy. MacIntyre largely won that battle, editing a magazine that required that every byline have an advanced medical degree{{what|date=May 2015}}, that cover models should look healthy rather than sexy, and that sexist language be avoided.{{cn|date=May 2015}} Christine MacIntyre was the editor-in-chief until her death in 1988. Tara Kraft is the current editor-in-chief. ''Shape'' found a readership based on that formula.
Weider was purchased by [[American Media (publisher)|American Media]] in 2002. A [[Germany|German]] version of ''Shape'' is available in Germany, Austria and Switzerland. The magazine is also edited in Romania.
On January 28, 2015, it was reported that ''Shape'' would be acquired by Meredith Corp. and ''[[Fitness (magazine)|Fitness]]'', published by the company, would cease publication in May 2015 and be combined with it.<ref>Tess Stynes, ''The Wall Street Journal''. [https://www.wsj.com/articles/meredith-to-acquire-shape-magazine-brand-1422458384 "Meredith to Acquire Shape Magazine Brand"] January 28, 2015. Retrieved January 29, 2015.</ref><ref name="adage">{{cite news|author1=Michael Sebastian|title=Meredith to Acquire Shape Magazine from American Media|url=http://adage.com/article/media/meredith-acquire-shape-magazine-american-media/296855/|accessdate=February 6, 2016|work=AdAge|date=January 28, 2015}}</ref>
==Content== Sections in the magazine include Features & Cover Stories, Shape Your Life, Look Great, Live Healthy, Get Fit, Eat Right, You In Shape, and In Every Issue, which includes From the Editor’s Desk, Contributors, Readers Speak Out, The Hot List and Fit & Famous.{{cn|date=May 2015}}
Other topics include sex, mind/spirit, beauty, travel, fashion, work, home and style.{{cn|date=May 2015}}
